# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: class-consciousness
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:class-consciousness/1819-balloon-riot] The **Philadelphia Balloon Riot** occurred at Vauxhall Garden in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania on the evening of September 8, 1819.
[src:class-consciousness/1819-balloon-riot] After guards beat a boy unconscious for attempting to climb a fence separating the paying guests from those who couldn't afford the expensive entry fee, crowds broke down the fence and ripped the hot air balloon to pieces.
[src:class-consciousness/1819-balloon-riot] In the early 1800s, Balloon aviation was a novel phenomenon in the U.S.
[src:class-consciousness/1819-balloon-riot] The first manned flight in a U.S. balloon was accomplished by Edward Warren in nearby Baltimore in 1784.
[src:class-consciousness/1819-balloon-riot] In September 1819 the *Franklin Gazette* of Philadelphia announced that French aeronaut Monsieur Michel would perform a balloon ascension and parachute leap at Vauxhall Garden.
[src:class-consciousness/1819-balloon-riot] Tens of thousands arrived to witness the balloon launch, but the one dollar admission fee (equal to $24.77 in 2024) prevented all but the wealthy from taking a closer look at the balloon.
[src:class-consciousness/1819-balloon-riot] Given the nature of hot air balloon technology at the time, the success or failure of a given balloon flight was uncertain and thus created significant suspense.
[src:class-consciousness/1819-balloon-riot] Due to "insufficient gas," the balloon at Vauxhall Gardens did not inflate properly and did not rise which further annoyed the waiting crowd.
[src:class-consciousness/1819-balloon-riot] Frustrated onlookers threw stones and punctured the balloon, whilst others attempted to climb the fence blocking the view.
[src:class-consciousness/1819-balloon-riot] One of these, a boy of fourteen, attempted to climb the fence and was quickly attacked by security guards.
[src:class-consciousness/1819-balloon-riot] The sight of the boy, beaten unconscious, aroused the anger of the crowd.
[src:class-consciousness/1819-balloon-riot] The exact causes of the Philadelphia Balloon Riot are uncertain.
[src:class-consciousness/1819-balloon-riot] Paul Gilje considers the Philadelphia Balloon Riot to be an example of class conscious rioting, mainly caused by the visible divisions between those who could pay for better access to the balloon and those who could not.
[src:class-consciousness/1819-balloon-riot] Other scholars suggest that the overreaction of local authorities was an important factor in the riot, stressing the beating of the boy as the primary cause.
[src:class-consciousness/1819-balloon-riot] Upon seeing the bloodied body of the boy, the crowd took action.
[src:class-consciousness/1819-balloon-riot] With the flagpole from the gardens as a makeshift battering ram, the crowd destroyed the gate.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] The **1934 West Coast waterfront strike** (also known as the **1934 West Coast longshoremen's strike**, as well as a number of variations on these names) began on May 9, 1934, when longshoremen in every U.S.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] The result of the strike was the unionization of all of the West Coast ports of the United States.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] The 1916 West Coast waterfront strike was the first instance of coastwide organizational unity among West Coast longshore workers.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] The strike resulted in a massive defeat for the ILA and employers launching an effort to eliminate the ILA's presence on the waterfront entirely.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] In the years immediately after World War I, when the shipping companies and stevedoring firms had imposed the open shop after a series of failed strikes, longshoremen on the West Coast ports were unorganized or represented by company unions.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] Longshoremen in San Francisco, then the major port on the coast, were required to go through a hiring hall operated by a company union, known as the "blue book" system for the color of the membership book.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] The Industrial Workers of the World, nicknamed "Wobblies," had attempted to organize longshoremen, sailors and fishermen in the 1920s through their Marine Transport Workers Union.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] Their largest strike, the 1923 San Pedro Maritime Strike, stalled shipping in that harbor but was crushed by a combination of injunctions, mass arrests and vigilantism by the American Legion.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] Other Wobbly-led strikes occurred in Seattle in 1919 and Portland in 1922.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] While the IWW was a spent force after that strike, syndicalist thinking remained popular on the docks.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] Longshoremen and sailors on the West Coast also had contacts with an Australian syndicalist movement that called itself the "One Big Union" formed after the defeat of a general strike there in 1917.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] The Communist Party had also been active in the area in the late 1920s, seeking to organize all categories of maritime workers into a single union, the Marine Workers Industrial Union (MWIU), as part of the drive during the Third Period to create revolutionary unions.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] The MWIU never made much headway on the West Coast, but it did attract a number of former IWW members and foreign-born militants.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] Harry Bridges, an Australian-born sailor who became a longshoreman after coming to the United States and played an instrumental role in organizing the 1934 strike, was often alleged to be an active member of the Communist party.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] Militants published a newspaper, *The Waterfront Worker*, which focused on longshoremen's most pressing demands: more men on each gang, lighter loads and an independent union.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] Grassroots reform of the ILA locals would gradually marginalize the MWIU.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] Just as the passage of the National Industrial Recovery Act had led to a spontaneous significant rise in union membership among coal miners in 1933, thousands of longshoremen now joined the fledgling ILA locals that reappeared on the West Coast.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] The MWIU declined as Communist Party activists were absorbed into the ILA.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] These newly emboldened workers first went after the "blue book" union, refusing to pay dues to it and tearing up their membership books.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] The militants who had published "The Waterfront Worker", now known as the "Albion Hall group" after their usual meeting place, continued organizing dock committees that soon began launching slowdowns and other types of job actions in order to win better working conditions.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] While the official leadership of the ILA remained in the hands of conservatives sent to the West Coast by President Joseph P.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] Ryan of the ILA, the Albion Hall group started in March, 1934 to press demands for a coastwide contract, a union-run hiring hall and an industry wide waterfront federation.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] When the conservative ILA leadership negotiated a weak "gentlemen's agreement" with the employers that had been brokered by the mediation board created by the administration of President Franklin D.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] Roosevelt, Bridges led the membership in rejecting it.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] Disputes revolved around the issue of recognition: the union demanded a closed shop, a coastwide contract and a union hiring hall.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] The employers offered to arbitrate the dispute, but insisted that the union agree to an open shop as a condition of any agreement to arbitrate.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] The longshoremen rejected the proposal to arbitrate.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] The strike began on May 9, 1934, as longshoremen in every West Coast port walked out; sailors joined them several days later.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] The employers recruited strikebreakers, housing them on moored ships or in walled compounds and bringing them to and from work under police protection.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] Strikers attacked the stockade housing strikebreakers in San Pedro on May 15; police fired into the strikers, killing two and injuring many.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] The killing of Dick Parker created resentment up and down the coast.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] Daily similar smaller clashes broke out in San Francisco and Oakland, California, Portland, Oregon, and Seattle, Washington.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] Strikers also succeeded in slowing down or stopping the movement of goods by rail out of the ports.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] The Roosevelt administration tried again to broker a deal to end the strike, but the membership twice rejected the agreements their leadership brought to them and continued the strike.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] The employers then decided to make a show of force to reopen the port in San Francisco.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] On Tuesday, July 3, fights broke out along the Embarcadero in San Francisco between police and strikers while a handful of trucks driven by young businessmen made it through the picket line.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] Some Teamsters supported the strikers by refusing to handle "hot cargo" – goods which had been unloaded by strikebreakers – although the Teamsters' leadership was not as supportive.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] By the end of May, Dave Beck, president of the Seattle Teamsters, and Mike Casey, president of those in San Francisco, thought the maritime strike had lasted too long.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] They encouraged the strikers to take what they could get from the employers and threatened to use Teamsters as strikebreakers if the ILA did not return to work.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] Shipping companies, government officials, some union leaders and the press began to raise fears that the strike was the result of communist agitation.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] After a quiet Fourth of July, the employers' organization, the Industrial Association, tried to open the port of San Francisco even further on Thursday, July 5.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] As spectators watched from Rincon Hill, the police shot tear gas canisters into the crowd, then followed with a charge by mounted police Picketers threw the canisters and rocks back at the police, who charged again, sending the picketers into retreat.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] Each side then refortified and took stock.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] The events took an even more violent turn that afternoon, as hostilities resumed outside of the ILA strike kitchen.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] Eyewitness accounts differ on the exact events that transpired next.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] According to some witnesses, a group of strikers first surrounded a police car and attempted to tip it over, prompting the police to fire shotguns in the air, and then revolvers at the crowd.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] Other eyewitness accounts claim that police officers started shooting in the direction of the strikers, provoking strikers to defend themselves.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] Policemen fired a shotgun into the crowd, striking three men in intersection of Steuart and Mission streets.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] One of the men, Howard Sperry, a striking longshoreman, later died of his wounds.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] Another man, Charles Olsen, was also shot but later recovered from his wounds.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] A third man, Nick Bordoise – a Greek by birth (originally named Nick Counderakis) who was an out of work member of the cook's union volunteering at the ILA strike kitchen – was shot but managed to make his way around the corner onto Spear Street, where he was found several hours later.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] Strikers immediately cordoned off the area where the two picketers had been shot, laying flowers and wreaths around it.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] Police arrived to remove the flowers and drive off the picketers minutes later.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] Once the police left, the strikers returned, replaced the flowers and stood guard over the spot.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] Though Sperry and Bordoise had been shot several blocks apart, this spot became synonymous with the memory of the two slain men and "Bloody Thursday".
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] As strikers carried wounded picketers into the ILA union hall police fired on the hall and lobbed tear gas canisters at nearby hotels.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] At this point someone reportedly called the union hall to ask "Are you willing to arbitrate now?".
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] Under orders from California Governor Frank Merriam, the California National Guard moved in that evening to patrol the waterfront.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] Similarly, federal soldiers of the United States Army stationed at the Presidio were placed on alert.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] The picketers pulled back, unwilling to take on armed soldiers in an uneven fight, and trucks and trains began moving without interference.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] Bridges asked the San Francisco Labor Council to meet that Saturday, July 7, to authorize a general strike.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] The Alameda County Central Labor Council in Oakland considered the same action.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] Teamsters in both San Francisco and Oakland voted to strike, over the objections of their leaders, on Sunday, July 8.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] The following day, several thousand strikers, families and sympathizers took part in a funeral procession down Market Street, stretching more than a mile and a half, for Nicholas Bordoise and Howard Sperry, the two persons killed on "Bloody Thursday".
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] The police were wholly absent from the scene.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] The Teamsters had already been out for two days by that point.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] San Francisco Mayor Angelo Rossi declared a state of emergency.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] Some federal officials, particularly Secretary of Labor Frances Perkins, were more skeptical.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] Roosevelt later recalled that some persons were urging him to steer the USS *Houston*, which was carrying him to Hawaii, "into San Francisco Bay, all flags flying and guns double-shotted, and end the strike." Roosevelt rejected the suggestion.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] The general strike began on the 16th, involving some 150,000 workers.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] On the 17th the police arrested more than 300 "radicals, subversives, and communists" while systematically smashing furniture and equipment of organizations related to the strike; the same day, General Hugh S.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] Johnson as head of the National Recovery Administration spoke at UC Berkeley to denounce the general strike as "a menace to the government".
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] Non-union truck drivers joined the first day; the movie theaters and night clubs closed down.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] While food deliveries continued with the permission of the strike committee, many small businesses closed, posting signs in support of the strikers.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] Reports that unions in Portland and Seattle would also begin general strikes picked up currency.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] The calling of a general strike had an unexpected result: it gave the General Strike Committee, whose makeup was far less militant than the longshoremen's strike committee, effective control over the maritime strike itself.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] Kidwell of the Bakery Wagon Drivers' Union, Michael Casey of the Teamsters, and Edward D.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] Vandeleur of the San Francisco Labor Council, all of whom opposed the calls by Bridges for a general strike.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] They used their positions on the committee to defuse class divisions and guide both sides toward arbitration.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] After four days, the Labor Council voted to end the strike.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] When it did so, it also recommended that the unions accept arbitration of all disputed issues.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] When the National Longshore Board put the employer's proposal to arbitrate to a vote of striking longshoremen, it passed in every port except Everett, Washington.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] That, however, left the striking seamen in the lurch: the employers had refused to arbitrate with the ISU unless it first won elections on the fleets on strike.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] On July 17, 1934, the California National Guard blocked both ends of Jackson Street from Drumm to Front with machine gun mounted trucks to assist vigilante raids, protected by SFPD, on the headquarters of the Marine Workers' Industrial Union and the ILA soup kitchen at 84 Embarcadero.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] Moving on, the Workers' Ex-Servicemen's League's headquarters on Howard between Third and Fourth was raided, leading to 150 arrests and the complete destruction of the facilities.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] The employer's group, the Industrial Association, had agents riding with the police.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] Further raids were carried out at the Workers' Open Forum at 1223 Fillmore street and the Western Worker building opposite City Hall that contained a bookstore and the main offices of the Communist Party, which was thoroughly destroyed.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] Attacks were also perpetrated on the 121 Haight Street Workers' School and the Mission Workers' Neighborhood House at 741 Valencia Street.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] A police spokesperson suggested that "maybe the Communists staged the raids themselves for publicity".
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] Johnson, then head of the National Recovery Administration, gave a speech urging responsible labor leaders to "run these subversive influences out from its ranks like rats".
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] A lawyer for the American Civil Liberties Union was kidnapped and beaten, while vigilantes seized thirteen radicals in San Jose and turned them over to the sheriff of an adjoining county, who transported them to another county.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] In Hayward in Alameda County someone erected a scaffold in front of the city hall with a noose and a sign stating "Reds beware" In Piedmont, an upscale community surrounded by Oakland on all sides, the chief of police prepared for a reported attack by strikers on the homes of wealthy ship-owners.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] While some of the most powerful people in San Francisco considered the strike's denouement to be a victory for the employers, many longshoremen and seamen did not.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] Spontaneous strikes over grievances and workplace conditions broke out as strikers returned to their jobs, with longshoremen and teamsters supporting their demands.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] Employers conceded many of these battles, giving workers even more confidence in demanding that employers lighten unbearably heavy loads.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] Longshoremen also began dictating other terms, fining members who worked more than the ceiling of 120 hours per month, filing charges against a gang boss for "slandering colored brothers" and forcing employers to fire strikebreakers.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] Other unions went further: the Marine Firemen proposed to punish any member who bought a Hearst newspaper.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] The arbitration award issued on October 12, 1934, cemented the ILA's power.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] While the award put the operation of the hall in the hands of a committee of union and employer representatives, the union was given the power to select the dispatcher.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] Since longshoremen were prepared to walk out if an employer did not hire a worker dispatched from the hall, the ILA soon controlled hiring on the docks.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] The employers complained that the union wanted to "sovietize" the waterfront.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] Workers complained that the employers were exploiting them for cheap labor and forcing them to work in unsafe conditions without reasonable safety measures.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] The union soon utilized the "quickie strike" tactic to force many concessions from employers such as safer working conditions and better pay.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] Similarly, even though an arbitrator held that the 1935 Agreement prohibited sympathy strikes, the union's members nonetheless refused to cross other unions' picket lines.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] Longshoremen also refused to handle "hot cargo" destined for non-union warehouses that the union was attempting to organize.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] The ISU acquired similar authority over hiring, despite the philosophical objection of the union's own officers to hiring halls.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] The ISU used this power to drive strikebreakers out of the industry.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] Before the strike, Black workers had managed to gain some leadership positions in the ILA's Seattle local.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] Afterward, credit for the strike's success was shared between Black and white longshoremen, and Black members gained further leadership positions.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] This contributed to Black longshoremen becoming some of the most powerful advocates for civil rights in the Western U.S.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] The arbitration award also gave longshoremen a raise to ninety-five cents ($23 in 2025 dollars) an hour for straight time work, just shy of the dollar an hour it demanded during the strike.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] It was also awarded a contract that applied up and down the West Coast.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] The strike also prompted union organizer Carmen Lucia to organize the Department Store Workers Union and the Retail Clerks Association in San Francisco.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] The ILWU continues to recognize "Bloody Thursday" by shutting down all West Coast ports every July 5 and honoring Nick Bordoise, Howard Sperry and all of the other workers killed by police during the strike.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] The ILWU has frequently stopped work for political protests against, among other things, Italy's invasion of Ethiopia, fascist intervention in the Spanish Civil War, South Africa's system of apartheid and the Iraq War.
[src:class-consciousness/1934-west-coast-waterfront-strike] Sam Kagel, the last surviving member of the original union steering committee, died on May 21, 2007, at the age of 98.
[src:class-consciousness/21st-century-communist-theorists] In the 21st-century there has been a revival of serious interest in communism, led by Slavoj Žižek and Alain Badiou.
[src:class-consciousness/21st-century-communist-theorists] This interest was propelled by the 2008 financial crisis which saw many books published offering communist and Marxist analyses of the crisis, and the 2009 conference "The Idea of Communism", that brought together many of theorists.
[src:class-consciousness/21st-century-communist-theorists] The interest in 21st-century theorists writing about communism spans a broad range of communist traditions.
[src:class-consciousness/21st-century-communist-theorists] According to the political theorist Alan Johnson, there has been a revival of serious interest in communism in the 21st century led by Slavoj Žižek and Alain Badiou.
[src:class-consciousness/21st-century-communist-theorists] In 2009, many advocates for and theorists of communism in the 21st century contributed to the three-day conference, "The Idea of Communism", in London that drew a substantial paying audience.
[src:class-consciousness/21st-century-communist-theorists] Journals such as *Endnotes*, *Salvage, Ebb Magazine* *Kites* and *Historical Materialism* launched with communist outlooks, as well as news outlets such as Novara Media.
[src:class-consciousness/21st-century-communist-theorists] Furthermore, internet culture and declining life prospects has led to a general rise amongst Millennials and Gen-Z in support for communism and socialism, in tandem with the rise of left-populism in the US and the UK.
[src:class-consciousness/21st-century-communist-theorists] Explicitly left-wing contemporary artists, such as filmmakers, musicians, video-game creators and comedians have received widespread attention, such as the rapper/producer JPEGMafia, and a whole media-creator ecosystem has developed around the online left, known as BreadTube.
[src:class-consciousness/21st-century-communist-theorists] Other non-Marxist thinkers who have also had an effect on the 'new communists' include the revolutionaries Subcomandante Marcos and Abdullah Öcalan, abolitionist Ruth Wilson Gilmore, economist Frédéric Lordon, architecture journalist Owen Hatherley, and the late anthropologist David Graeber.
[src:class-consciousness/21st-century-communist-theorists] According to Slavoj Žižek, the book *Empire* by the autonomists Michael Hardt and Antonio Negri, was a major turning stone in 21st-century Marxist and communist thought.
[src:class-consciousness/21st-century-communist-theorists] Theoretical publications, some published by Verso Books, include *The Idea of Communism*, edited by Costas Douzinas and Žižek; Badiou's *The Communist Hypothesis*; and Bosteels's *The Actuality of Communism*.
[src:class-consciousness/21st-century-communist-theorists] Communism as a radical philosophical idea.
[src:class-consciousness/21st-century-communist-theorists] It must be thought of as taking distance from economism and statism as well as learning from the experiences of the 21st century.
[src:class-consciousness/21st-century-communist-theorists] Communism combats neoliberalism by returning to the idea of the "common".
[src:class-consciousness/21st-century-communist-theorists] Equality cannot exist without freedom and vice versa.
[src:class-consciousness/21st-century-communist-theorists] A rise in Marxist thought followed the 2008 financial crisis, with the publishing of books including G.
[src:class-consciousness/21st-century-communist-theorists] Cohen's *Why Not Socialism?* (2009), Paul Paolucci's *Marx's Scientific Dialectics* (2009), Kieran Allen's *Marx and the Alternative to Capitalism* (2011), Terry Eagleton's *Why Marx Was Right* (2011) and Vincent Mosco's *Marx Is Back* (2012).
[src:class-consciousness/21st-century-communist-theorists] *The Communist Horizon*, published in 2012 by Jodi Dean, marked the beginning in a series of books from Dean which argue for the necessity of communist and Leninist politics.
[src:class-consciousness/a-contribution-to-the-critique-of-political-economy] Much of the *Critique* was later incorporated by Marx into his *magnum opus*, *Capital* (Volume I), published in 1867, and the *Critique* is generally considered to be of secondary importance among Marx's writings.
[src:class-consciousness/a-contribution-to-the-critique-of-political-economy] This does not apply, however, to the Preface of the *Critique*.
[src:class-consciousness/a-contribution-to-the-critique-of-political-economy] Marx expressed this himself in the preface of the book: "It is not the consciousness of men that determines their being, but, on the contrary, their social being that determines (German: *bestimmt*, lit.
[src:class-consciousness/a-contribution-to-the-critique-of-political-economy] In English, *A Contribution to the Critique of Political Economy* is available in an edition edited by Maurice Dobb, published by Progress Publishers, Moscow (translation by S.
[src:class-consciousness/a-contribution-to-the-critique-of-political-economy] Lawrence and Wishart (London), and International Publishers (New York) cooperated in the publication of the Progress Publishers edition.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] Öcalan was based in Syria from 1979 to 1998.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] He helped found the PKK in 1978, and led it into the Kurdish–Turkish conflict in 1984.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] For most of his leadership, he was based in Syria, which provided sanctuary to the PKK until the late 1990s.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] The sentence was commuted to aggravated life imprisonment when Turkey abolished the death penalty.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] From 1999 until 2009, he was the sole prisoner in İmralı prison in the Sea of Marmara, where he is still held.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] Öcalan has advocated for a political solution to the conflict since the 1993 Kurdistan Workers' Party ceasefire. Öcalan's prison regime has oscillated between long periods of isolation during which he is allowed no contact with the outside world, and periods when he is permitted visits.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] He was also involved in negotiations with the Turkish government that led to a temporary Kurdish–Turkish peace process in 2013.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] In February 2025, he issued a statement from prison calling on the PKK to disarm and disband itself, after which the group's leadership declared a unilateral ceasefire.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] From prison, Öcalan has published several books.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] While some sources report his date of birth as 4 April 1949, no official birth records exist.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] He has claimed not to know exactly when he was born, estimating the year to be 1946 or 1947.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] He is the oldest of seven children. Öcalan's father was poor even by local standards, and he once said that there was "always fighting" and "an overwhelming unhappiness" in his family.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] When asked about their ethnic origin, his younger brother Osman Öcalan stated that their paternal family was fully Kurdish, while their maternal family was of mixed Kurdish, Turkish, Arab, and Assyrian origins.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] While Abdullah Öcalan claimed that their mother was fully Turkmen, Osman Öcalan disputed it, stating that many Albanian and other Balkan migrants were imported to the region by the Ottomans and identified as Turks, although he did not fully dismiss the possibility of their mother being Turkish.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] After the death of Abdi Ağa, Hüseyin Ağa led more revenge attacks on the Ottomans and drove them away.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] The family was celebrated by other Kurds and known as "Mala Ocê" ("House of Revenge").
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] After the Surname Law, the surname was Turkified to "Öcalan", meaning "revengeful".
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] Abdullah Öcalan spoke only Kurdish until elementary school, which he attended in a neighboring village.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] After he began school, he learned Turkish and began assimilating.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] He was impacted by Turkish nationalist school curriculum and dreamed of joining the Turkish army when he grew up.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] He applied to a military high school for future commissioned officers, but had failed the admission exam.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] Rejected from the military high school, Öcalan enrolled in a vocational high school in Ankara (Turkish: *Ankara Tapu-Kadastro Meslek Lisesi*) in 1966.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] After graduating in 1969, Öcalan began working at the Title Deeds Office of Diyarbakır.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] It was at this time his political affiliation began to reform.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] He was relocated one year later to Istanbul where he participated in the meetings of the Revolutionary Cultural Eastern Hearths (DDKO), a Kurdish organization.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] Later, he entered the Istanbul Law Faculty but after the first year transferred to Ankara University to study political science.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] According to a book by journalist Necdet Pekmezci, Öcalan's return to Ankara was facilitated by the state in order to divide the *Dev-Genç* (Revolutionary Youth Federation of Turkey), of which Öcalan was a member.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] President Süleyman Demirel later regretted this decision, since the PKK was to become a much greater threat to the state than *Dev-Genç*.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] Öcalan was not able to graduate from Ankara University, as on 7 April 1972 he was arrested after participating in a rally against the killing of Mahir Çayan.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] He was charged with distributing the left-wing political magazine *Şafak* (published by Doğu Perinçek) and was held for seven months at the Mamak Prison.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] In November 1973, the Ankara Democratic Association of Higher Education, (*Ankara Demokratik Yüksek Öğrenim Demeği,* ADYÖD) was founded and shortly after he was elected to join its board.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] In the ADYÖD several students close to the political views of Hikmet Kıvılcımlı were active.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] In December 1974, *ADYÖD* was closed down.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] In 1975, together with Mazlum Doğan and Mehmet Hayri Durmuş, he published a political booklet which described the main aims for a *Revolution in Kurdistan*.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] During meetings in Ankara between 1974 and 1975, Öcalan and others came to the conclusion that Kurdistan was a colony and preparations ought to be made for a revolution.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] The group decided to disperse into the different towns in Turkish Kurdistan in order to set up a base of supporters for an armed revolution.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] At the beginning, this idea had only a few supporters, but following a journey Öcalan made through the cities of Ağrı, Batman, Diyarbakır, Bingöl, Kars and Urfa in 1977, the group counted over 300 adherents and had organised about thirty armed militants.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] In 1978, in the midst of the right- and left-wing conflicts which culminated in the 1980 Turkish coup d'état, Öcalan founded the Kurdistan Workers' Party (PKK).
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] Since its foundation, the party focused on ideological training.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] "If you break the link between yourself and ideology you will beastialize," he told his followers.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] With the support of the Syrian Government, he established two training camps for the PKK in Lebanon where the Kurdish guerrillas should receive political and military training.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] In 1984, the PKK initiated a campaign of armed conflict by attacking government forces in order to create an independent Kurdish state. Öcalan attempted to unite the Kurdish liberation movements of the PKK and the one active against Saddam Hussein in Iraq.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] In negotiations between the Kurdistan Democratic Party (KDP) and the PKK, it was agreed that the latter was able to move freely in Iraqi Kurdistan.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] He also met twice with Masoud Barzani, the leader of the KDP in Damascus, to resolve some minor issues they had once in 1984 and another time in 1985.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] But due to pressure from Turkey the cooperation remained timid.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] During an interview he gave to the Turkish Milliyet in 1988, he mentioned the goal wasn't to gain independence from Turkey at all costs, but remained firm on the issue of the Kurdish rights, and suggested that negotiations should take place for a federation to be established in Turkey.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] In 1988, he also met with Jalal Talabani of the Patriotic Union of Kurdistan (PUK) in Damascus, with which he signed an agreement and after some differences after the foundation of a Kurdish Government in Iraqi Kurdistan in 1992 he later had a better relationship.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] In the early 1990s, interviews given to both Doğu Perinçek and Hasan Bildirici he mentioned his willingness to achieve a peaceful solution to the conflict.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] In another given to Oral Çalışlar, he emphasized the difference between independence and separatism.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] He articulated the view that different nations were able to live in independence within the same state if they had equal rights.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] Then in 1993, upon request of Turkish president Turgut Özal, Öcalan met with Jalal Talabani for negotiations following which Öcalan declared a unilateral cease fire which had a duration from 20 March to 15 April.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] Later he prolonged it in order to enable negotiations with the Turkish government.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] Soon after Özal died on 17 April 1993, the initiative was halted by Turkey on the grounds that Turkey did not negotiate with terrorists.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] During an International Kurdish Conference in Brussels in March 1994, his initiative for equal rights for Kurds and Turks within Turkey was discussed.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] It is reported by Gottfried Stein, that at least during the first half of the 1990s, he used to live mainly in a protected neighborhood in Damascus.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] On 7 May 1996, in the midst of another unilateral cease-fire declared by the PKK, an attempt to assassinate him in a house in Damascus, was unsuccessful.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] Following the protests which arose against the prohibition of the PKK in Germany, Öcalan had several meetings with politicians from Germany who came to hold talks with him.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] Back in Germany, Lummer made a statement in support for further negotiations with Öcalan.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] With time, the United States (1997), European Union, Syria, Turkey, and other countries have included the PKK on their lists of terrorist organizations.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] A Greek parliamentary delegation from the PASOK came to visit him in the Beqaa valley on 17 October 1996.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] During his stay in Syria he has published several books concerning the Kurdish revolution.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] On at least one occasion, in 1993, he was detained and held by Syria's General Intelligence Directorate, but later released.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] As the situation deteriorated in Turkey, the Turkish government openly threatened Syria over its support for the PKK.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] As a result, the Syrian government forced Öcalan to leave the country but still refused turning him over to the Turkish authorities.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] In October 1998, Öcalan prepared for his departure from Syria and during a meeting in Kobane, he unsuccessfully attempted to lay the foundations for a new party which failed due to Syrian intelligence's obstruction.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] Öcalan left Syria on 9 October 1998 and for the next four months, he toured several European countries advocating for a solution of the Kurdish-Turkish conflict. Öcalan first went to Russia where the Russian parliament voted on 4 November 1998 to grant him asylum.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] On 6 November 109 Greek parliamentarians invited Öcalan to stay in Greece, a move which was repeated by Panayioitis Sgouridis, the deputy speaker of the Greek Parliament at the time. Öcalan then chose to travel to Italy, where he landed on 12 November 1998 at the airport in Rome.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] In 1998 the Turkish government requested the extradition of Öcalan from Italy, where he applied for political asylum upon his arrival.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] He was detained by the Italian authorities due to an arrest warrant issued by Germany.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] But Italy did not extradite him to Germany, who refused to hold a trial on Öcalan in its country.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] The German chancellor Gerhard Schröder as well as the Minister of the Interior Otto Schily preferred that Öcalan would be tried by an unspecified "European Court".
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] Italy also didn't extradite him to Turkey.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] The Italian prime minister Massimo D'Alema announced it was contrary to Italian law to extradite someone to a country where the defendant is threatened with a capital punishment.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] But Italy also didn't want Öcalan to stay, and pulled several diplomatic strings to compel him to leave the country, which was accomplished on 16 January when he departed to Nizhny Novgorod in hope to find a safe haven in Russia.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] But in Russia he was not as much welcomed as in October, and he had to wait for a week at the airport of Strigino International Airport in Nizhny Novgorod.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] From Russia, he took an airplane from Saint Petersburg to Greece where he arrived in Athens upon the invitation of Nikolas Naxakis, a retired Admiral on 29 January 1999.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] He spent the night as a guest of the popular Greek author Voula Damianakou in Nea Makri.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] At that time he was defended by Britta Böhler, a high-profile German attorney who argued that the crimes he was accused of would have to be proven in court and attempted to reach that the International Court in The Hague would assume the case.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] Öcalan was abducted in Kenya on 15 February 1999, while on his way from the Greek embassy to Jomo Kenyatta International Airport in Nairobi, in an operation by the Turkish National Intelligence Organization (Turkish: *Millî İstihbarat Teşkilatı**,* MIT), with the help of the CIA.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] Following his capture, the Greek Government was in turmoil and Foreign Minister Theodoros Pangalos, Interior Minister Alekos Papadopoulos and the Minister of Public Order Philipos Petsalnikos resigned from their posts.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] Costoulas, the Greek ambassador who protected him, said that his own life was in danger after the operation.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] Kurds living in Germany were threatened with deportation if they continued to hold demonstrations in support of Öcalan.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] The warning came after three Kurds were killed and 16 injured during the 1999 attack on the Israeli consulate in Berlin.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] A group named the *Revenge Hawks of Apo* set fire to a department store in Kadıköy Istanbul, causing the death of 13 people.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] In several European capitals and larger cities as well as in Iraq, Iran and also Turkey protests were organized against his capture.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] He was brought to İmralı island, where he was interrogated for a period of 10 days without being allowed to see or speak to his lawyers.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] A state security court consisting of one military and two civilian judges was established on İmralı island to try Öcalan.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] A delegation of three Dutch lawyers who intended to defend him were not allowed to meet with their client and detained for questioning at the airport on the grounds that they acted as "PKK militants" and not lawyers; they were sent back to the Netherlands.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] On the seventh day a judge took part in the interrogations, and prepared a transcript of it.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] The trial began on 31 May 1999 on the İmralı island in the Sea of Marmara, and was organized by the Ankara State Security Court.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] During the trial, he was represented by the Asrın Law Office.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] His lawyers had difficulty in representing him adequately as they were allowed only two interviews per week of initially a duration of 20 minutes, and later 1 hour, of which several were cancelled due to "bad weather" or because the authorities didn't give the permission needed for them.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] Also his lawyers were unaware of what the charges might be, and received the formal indictment only after excerpts of it were already presented to the press.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] The trial was accompanied by arrests of scores of Kurdish politicians from the People's Democracy Party (HADEP).
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] In mid-June 1999, the Grand National Assembly of Turkey approved the removal of military judges from the State Security Courts, in an attempt to address criticism from the European Court of Human Rights and a civilian judge assumed the post of the military judge.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] Shortly before the verdict was read out by Judge Turgut Okyay, when asked about his final remarks, he again offered to play a role in the peace finding process. Öcalan was charged with treason and separatism and sentenced to death on 29 June 1999.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] He was also banned from holding public office for life.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] On the same day, Amnesty International (AI) demanded a re-trial and Human Rights Watch (HRW) questioned the fact that witnesses brought by the defense were not heard in the trial.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] In 1999 the Turkish Parliament discussed a so-called Repentance Bill which would commute Öcalans death sentence to 20 years imprisonment and allow PKK militants to surrender with a limited amnesty, but it didn't pass due to resistance from the far-right around the Nationalist Movement Party (MHP).
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] In January 2000 the Turkish government declared the death sentence was delayed until the European Court of Human Rights (ECHR) reviewed the verdict.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] Upon the abolition of the death penalty in Turkey in August 2002, in October of that year, the security court commuted his sentence to life imprisonment.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] In an attempt to reach a verdict which was more favorable to Öcalan, he appealed at the ECHR at Strasbourg, which accepted the case in June 2004.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] In 2005, the ECHR ruled that Turkey had violated articles 3, 5, and 6 of the European Convention of Human Rights by refusing to allow Öcalan to appeal his arrest and by sentencing him to death without a fair trial. Öcalan's request for a retrial was refused by Turkish courts.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] After his capture, Öcalan was held in solitary confinement as the only prisoner on İmralı island in the Sea of Marmara.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] Following the commutation of the death sentence to a life sentence in 2002, Öcalan remained imprisoned on İmralı, and was the sole inmate there.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] Although former prisoners at İmralı were transferred to other prisons, more than 1,000 Turkish military personnel were stationed on the island to guard him.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] In November 2009, Turkish authorities announced that they were ending his solitary confinement by transferring several other prisoners to İmralı.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] They said that Öcalan would be allowed to see them for ten hours a week.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] The new prison was built after the Council of Europe's Committee for the Prevention of Torture visited the island and objected to the conditions in which he was being held.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] From 27 July 2011 until 2 May 2019 his lawyers have not been allowed to see Abdullah Öcalan.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] From July 2011 until December 2017 his lawyers filed more than 700 appeals for visits, but all were rejected.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] There have been held regular demonstrations by the Kurdish community to raise awareness of the isolation of Öcalan.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] In October 2012 several hundred Kurdish political prisoners went on hunger strike for better detention conditions for Öcalan and the right to use the Kurdish language in education and jurisprudence.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] The hunger strike lasted 68 days until Öcalan demanded its end. Öcalan was banned from receiving visits almost two years from 6 October 2014 until 11 September 2016, when his brother Mehmet Öcalan visited him for Eid al-Adha.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] In 2014 the ECHR ruled in that there was a violation of article 3 in regards of him being to only prisoner on İmarli island until 17 November 2009, as well as the impossibility to appeal his verdict.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] On 6 September 2018 visits from lawyers were banned for six months due to former punishments he received in the years 2005–2009, the fact that the lawyers made their conversations with Ocalan public, and the impression that Öcalan was leading the PKK through communications with his lawyers.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] He was again banned from receiving visits until 12 January 2019 when his brother was permitted to visit him a second time.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] The ban on the visitation of his lawyers was lifted in April 2019, and Öcalan saw his lawyers on 2 May 2019.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] In January 1999 during his stay in Europe, Öcalan saw the parties liberation struggle focus to have developed from guerrilla warfare to dialogue and negotiations.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] After his capture Öcalan called for a halt in PKK attacks, and advocated for a peaceful solution for the Kurdish conflict inside the borders of Turkey.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] In October 1999, eight PKK militants around the former European PKK spokesman Ali Sapan turned themselves in to Turkey on request of Öcalan.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] Depending on their treatment, the other PKK militants would turn themselves in as well, his attorney announced.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] A similar structure began functioning in May 2006.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] With this process, the way to democratic dialogue will be also opened".
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] Though the Turkish government had received Öcalan's protocols, they were never released to the public. Öcalan said he would leave the top PKK commanders in charge of the conflict, but that this should not be misinterpreted as a call for the PKK to intensify its armed conflict with Turkey.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] In January 2013, peace negotiations between the PKK and the Turkish Government were initiated and from between January and March he met several times with politicians of Peace and Democracy Party (BDP) on Imralı Island.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] On 21 March, Öcalan declared a ceasefire between the PKK and the Turkish state. Öcalan's statement was read to hundreds of thousands of Kurds in Diyarbakır who had gathered to celebrate the Kurdish New Year (*Newroz*).
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] The statement said in part, "Let guns be silenced and politics dominate... a new door is being opened from the process of armed conflict to democratization and democratic politics.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] It's the start of a new era." Soon after Öcalan's declaration, the functional head of the PKK, Murat Karayılan responded by promising to implement a ceasefire.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] During the peace process, the pro-Kurdish Peoples' Democratic Party (HDP) entered parliament during the parliamentarian election of June 2015.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] The ceasefire ended following the 2014 Kobanî protests and after two Turkish police officers were killed in Ceylanpınar in July 2015, leading to the 2015–2016 Kurdish–Turkish conflict.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] On 27 February 2025, Öcalan issued a message from prison calling for the PKK to hold a congress dissolving itself and lay down its weapons, kicking off the 2025 PKK–Turkey peace process.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] In response, the PKK announced that it had begun a ceasefire on 1 March.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] Following the PKK's decision to dissolve itself in May 2025, Öcalan issued a message the following month announcing the end of the PKK insurgency against the Turkish state.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] Since his incarceration, Öcalan has significantly changed his ideology through exposure to Western social theorists such as Murray Bookchin, Immanuel Wallerstein and Hannah Arendt.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] Abandoning his old Marxism–Leninist and Stalinist beliefs, Öcalan fashioned his ideal society called democratic confederalism.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] In early 2004, Öcalan attempted to arrange a meeting with Murray Bookchin through Öcalan's lawyers, describing himself as Bookchin's "student" eager to adapt Bookchin's thought to Middle Eastern society.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] Bookchin was too ill to meet with Öcalan.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] In this zone, three bodies of law would be implemented: EU law, Turkish/Syrian/Iraqi/Iranian law and Kurdish law.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] While some of his followers questioned Öcalan's conversion from Marxism-Leninism to social ecology, the PKK adopted Öcalan's proposal and began to form assemblies.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] All are welcome to partake in the communal councils, but political participation is not mandated.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] There is no private property, but rather "ownership by use, which grants individuals usage rights to the buildings, land, and infrastructure, but not the right to sell and buy on the market or convert them to private enterprises".
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] The economy is in the hands of the communal councils, and is thus (in the words of Bookchin) 'neither collectivised nor privatised - it is common.' Feminism, ecology, and direct democracy are essential in democratic confederalism.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] Parallel to Democratic Confederalism, Öcalan introduced the principle of the Brotherhood of Peoples in 2013, aimed at promoting peaceful coexistence between Kurds and other ethnic groups, similar to the Marxist concept of the friendship of peoples.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] During the 2025 PKK–Turkey peace process, Öcalan repeatedly emphasized the Brotherhood of Peoples, stating that it had "reached a threshold" and referring to a "1000-year-old" historical brotherhood between Kurds and Turks.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] Öcalan is a supporter of the liberation of the women, he writes in his Freedom Manifesto for Women that all slavery is based on the housewifization of women.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] He deems the woman often as being trapped in a situation where she accepts traditional gender roles and a disadvantaged relationship with a man.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] In the context of Turkey and the activities of the HDP, and now DEM Party, this approach has been described by as Turkeyification, which critics characterize as a form of voluntary Turkification.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] The Middle East Forum described Öcalan's stance in the 2025 PKK–Turkey peace process as paradoxical, noting that the PKK was originally founded in response to the denial of Kurdish existence in Turkey.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] Öcalan's Brotherhood of Peoples concept has also faced similar criticism.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] Some commentators have described it as a "project that was born rejected," particularly after Arab tribes defected from the Kurdish-led Syrian Democratic Forces (SDF) during the 2026 northeastern Syria offensive, which may have contributed to the collapse of the DAANES.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] During Öcalan's childhood, his mother, Esma Öcalan (Uveys) was rather dominant and criticised his father, blaming him for their dire economic situation.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] He later explained in an interview that it was in his childhood he learned to defend himself from injustice.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] Like many Kurds in Turkey, Öcalan was raised speaking Turkish; according to Amikam Nachmani, lecturer at the Bar-Ilan University in Israel, Öcalan did not know Kurdish when he met him in 1991.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] Nachmani: "*He [Öcalan] told me that he speaks Turkish, gives orders in Turkish, and thinks in Turkish."* In 1978 Öcalan married Kesire Yildirim, who he had met at the Ankara University and was of a better household than the regular revolutionaries around Öcalan.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] They had a difficult marriage with reportedly many disputes and discussions.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] In 1988, while representing the PKK in Athens, Greece, his wife unsuccessfully attempted to overthrow Öcalan, following which Yildirim went underground.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] After his sister Havva was married to a man from another village in an arranged marriage, he felt regret.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] This event led Öcalan to his policies towards the liberation of women from the traditional suppressed female role. Öcalan's brother Osman became a PKK commander until he defected from the PKK with several others to establish the Patriotic and Democratic Party of Kurdistan.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] His other brother, Mehmet Öcalan, is a member of the pro-Kurdish Peace and Democracy Party (BDP).
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] Fatma Öcalan is the sister of Abdullah Öcalan and Dilek Öcalan, a former parliamentarian of the HDP, is his niece. Ömer Öcalan, a current member of parliament for the HDP, is his nephew.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] Öcalan is the author of more than 40 books, four of which were written in prison.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] Many of the notes taken from his weekly meetings with his lawyers have been edited and published.
[src:class-consciousness/abdullah-öcalan] He has also written articles for the newspaper Özgür Gündem which is a newspaper that reported on the Kurdish-Turkish conflict, under the pseudonym of Ali Firat.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] Guzmán joined the Communist Party when he was about 20 years old.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] In the 1960s and 1970s, he was a professor of philosophy active in far-left politics strongly influenced by Marxism, Leninism, and Maoism.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] He developed an ideology of armed struggle stressing the empowerment of the Indigenous people.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] He went underground in the mid-1960s to become the leader of the Shining Path, which began "The People's War" or the "Armed Struggle" on 17 May 1980.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] Manuel Rubén Abimael Guzmán Reinoso was born on 3 December 1934 in Mollendo, a port town in the province of Islay, in the region of Arequipa, about 1,000 km (620 mi) south of Lima.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] He was the illegitimate son of an accountant who had ten children with five women.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] Guzmán's mother, Berenice Reinoso, died when he was five.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] At Arequipa, Guzmán completed bachelor's degrees in philosophy and law.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] His dissertations were titled *The Kantian Theory of Space* and *The Bourgeois Democratic State*.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] While in university, Guzmán became a Marxist–Leninist.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] In 1962, he was recruited as a professor of philosophy by the rector of San Cristóbal of Huamanga University in Ayacucho, Efraín Morote Best, an anthropologist who some believe was the true intellectual leader of the "Shining Path" movement.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] Encouraged by Morote, Guzmán studied Quechua, the language of Peru's Indigenous population, and became increasingly active in left-wing political circles.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] In 1965, Guzmán attended a cadre training course in China, returning to Lima and taking a leave of absence from his professorship to focus on party activism.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] In April 1967, he led his faction of the PCP to an international meeting in Albania.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] He returned to China in August and September.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] This placed him in China during the Cultural Revolution, which made a large impression on him.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] Guzmán was particularly influenced by the ideological position of the Gang of Four.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] Through his academic position, Guzmán developed a core of early supporters among rural teachers, university professors, and the university student movement.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] He was arrested twice during the 1970s for participating in violent riots in the city of Arequipa against the government of presidents Velasco Alvarado and Belaunde Terry.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] After serving as the head of personnel for San Cristóbal of Huamanga University, Guzmán left the institution in the mid-1960s and went underground.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] In the 1960s, the Peruvian Communist Party splintered over ideological and personal disputes.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] Guzmán, who had taken a pro-Chinese rather than pro-Soviet line, emerged as the leader of the faction that came to be known as the "Shining Path" (Mariátegui wrote once: "Marxism–Leninism is the shining path of the future").
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] In 1970, Bandera Roja expelled Guzmán because of his and his group's "occultism"—a Marxist-Leninist term for refusing or being unable to carry out open or legal political work and excessively focusing on covert activities.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] Guzmán adopted the *nom de guerre* Presidente or Comrade Gonzalo and began advocating a Maoist peasant-led revolution.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] His followers declared Guzmán, who cultivated anonymity, the "Fourth Sword of Communism" (after Lenin, Stalin and Mao).
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] He praised Mao's development of Lenin's thesis regarding "the role of imperialism" in propping up the "bourgeois capitalist system", claiming that imperialism ultimately "creates disruption and is unsuccessful, and it will end up in ruins in the next 50 to 100 years".
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] Guzmán applied this criticism not only to U.S. imperialism but also Soviet imperialism, what he called "social-imperialism" (in accordance with the Chinese stance after the Sino-Soviet split).
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] In February 1964, he married Augusta La Torre, who was instrumental in founding Shining Path.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] She died under unclear circumstances in 1988.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] Guzmán and Elena Yparraguirre, a longtime lieutenant of Guzmán's and his lover, have both refused to discuss La Torre's fate.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] In 2006, while in prison, Guzmán proposed to Yparraguirre, who is also serving a life sentence in a separate prison.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] After fighting for permission to marry with a hunger strike, the couple wed in 2010.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] He agreed with Karl Marx that religion is the "opium of the people" and said it would end with exploitation.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] But he requested respect for religious diversity and said religion would not be an obstacle for the armed struggle.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] The Shining Path movement was at first largely confined to academic circles in Peruvian universities.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] The 1976 downfall of the Gang of Four convinced Guzmán that China had become revisionist, and that communist revolution required the directing of a people's war that maintained ideological purity.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] In the late 1970s, the Shining Path movement developed into a guerrilla group centered around Ayacucho.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] In May 1980, the group launched its war against the government of Peru by burning the ballot boxes in Chuschi, a village near Ayacucho, in an effort to disrupt the first democratic elections in the country since 1964.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] Shining Path eventually grew to control vast rural territories in central and southern Peru and achieved a presence even in the outskirts of Lima, where it staged numerous attacks.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] The purpose of Shining Path's campaign was to demoralize and undermine the government of Peru in order to create a situation conducive to a violent coup which would put its leaders in power.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] The Truth and Reconciliation Commission later estimated that the resulting conflict led to the deaths of some seventy thousand people, approximately half of them at the hands of the Shining Path and a third at the hands of the state.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] Guzmán's image as a dispassionate murderer became widespread after he moved against the city of Lima.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] After a series of bombings and selective assassinations the whole nation was shocked in 1992 when a car bomb exploded in one of Lima's busiest commercial districts on Tarata street, thus causing many casualties and enormous material losses.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] Guzmán denied responsibility for the Tarata bombing, claiming it was carried out without his knowledge.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] Guzmán claimed that such an equilibrium would manifest itself by ungovernability under the "old order." When that moment arrived, Guzmán believed that Shining Path would be ready to move on to its "strategic offensive".
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] In the 1991 Peruvian Annual Power Survey, Guzmán was ranked fourth among the ten most powerful people in Peru, having been fifth in 1990.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] Soon, Guzmán believed the Peruvian People's War had entered a strategic stalemate, centering his views on the capital, Lima, as the "national level." He believed there were no capitalist roaders within the party, whom he considered exiled, and turned to Stalin, anticipating significant losses.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] In 1992, during the first administration of President Alberto Fujimori, the National Directorate Against Terrorism (DIRCOTE) began surveillance on several residences in Lima because agents suspected that terrorists were using them as safehouses.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] One of those residences, in the upper-class neighborhood of Surco, had been operating as a ballet studio.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] The DIRCOTE operatives routinely searched the garbage taken out from the house.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] The house was supposedly inhabited by only one person, the dance teacher Maritza Garrido Lecca, but it was soon noticed that the household produced more garbage than one person could account for.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] Furthermore, agents found discarded tubes of cream for the treatment of psoriasis, an ailment that Guzmán was known to have.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] On 12 September 1992, an elite unit of the DIRCOTE carried out Operation Victoria, raiding the Surco residence.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] On the second floor of the house, they found and arrested Guzmán and eight others, including Laura Zambrano and Elena Yparraguirre, Guzmán's female companion.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] Guzmán was tried by a military tribunal under provisions of articles 15 and 16 of Law 25475 adopted by Fujimori's government in May 1992.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] The identities of the judges were kept secret to Guzmán and the press, and proceedings were held in secret.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] After a three-day trial, Guzmán was sentenced to life imprisonment and incarcerated at the naval base on the island of San Lorenzo off the coast of Lima.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] Subsequently, he was said to have negotiated with a presidential advisor at the time, Vladimiro Montesinos, in order to receive some benefits in exchange for helping the Peruvian government put an end to the Shining Path's militant activities.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] Guzmán appeared several times on Peruvian television and on 1 October 1993, he publicly declared "peace" with the Peruvian government.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] This declaration split the Shining Path and raised questions about the organization's future.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] About 6,000 guerrillas within the party accepted it as a sign of defeat and surrendered.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] Guzmán's re-trial began on 5 November 2004.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] The international press was held in a sound-proof chamber and all media was banned from observing the trial after the Shining Path cadre turned their backs on the judges and delivered a revolutionary salute to the media gallery.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] The only words Guzmán spoke in the presence of the international press were "Long live the Communist Party of Peru!
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] Long live the heroes of the people's war!" After he made this statement, the courtroom microphones were silenced and the press was unable to hear any of the proceedings that followed.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] When the trial resumed on 12 November, no reporters were allowed to observe the proceedings.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] Eventually two of the judges recused themselves and the trial ended in chaos.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] Guzmán's third trial began in September 2005 and was opened and closed amid a media blackout.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] On 13 October 2006, Guzmán was sentenced to life in prison on charges of aggravated terrorism and murder.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] At his sentencing, three judges read the charges in a verdict that lasted more than six hours.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] In 2014, Guzmán and his wife Yparraguirre were tried again, for the 1992 Tarata bombing in Lima in which 25 people died.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] On 11 September 2018, he was sentenced to a second life term in prison.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] Guzmán was incarcerated in the maximum security prison of the naval base of Callao, the port of Lima, until his death in 2021.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] Fellow prisoners there include Víctor Polay, leader of the Túpac Amaru Revolutionary Movement, and Vladimiro Montesinos, the former head of the National Intelligence Service who supervised the construction of the prison and served under the President Alberto Fujimori.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] On 13 July 2021, he was attended by medical personnel of the Ministry of Health after he refused to eat.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] He was given blood tests and an ultrasound.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] A few days later, on 17 July, he was transferred to a hospital for further monitoring.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] He died on 11 September 2021 at the Maximum Safety Center of the Callao Naval Base, at the age of 86.
[src:class-consciousness/abimael-guzmán] Guzmán's body was cremated at sunrise on 24 September 2021 and his ashes were dispersed in a secret location in order to prevent a monument honoring him from being created.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] So, Marx argues that human work is both (1) an activity which, by its useful effect, helps to create particular kinds of products, and (2) in an economic sense, a *value-forming* activity that, if it is productively applied, can help create more value than there was before.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] If an employer hires labour, the employer thinks both about how useful the labour service will be for his business operations, and about the value that the labour can create for his business.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] That is, the right kind of work not only needs to get done, but it also needs to get done in a way that it helps the employer to make money.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] If the labour makes no net addition to new value produced, then the employer makes no money from it.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] The labour will be only an expense to him.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] If the labour is only a net expense (overhead), then it is commercially speaking *unproductive* labour.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] Yet, it may be very necessary to employ this unproductive labour.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] If that labour was not done, then considerable capital value might be *lost* from the employer's financial investments.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] Indeed, the business might fail without it.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] That is, labour may be very necessary to *maintain* capital value, although it does not actually *add* value to capital, and does not directly add to net profit.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] So, the employer also buys the "unproductive labour", because it reduces his costs.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] His labour costs will be lower than the *loss* of value that would occur, if he did not employ unproductive labour to *maintain* capital value, and to prevent loss of capital value.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] For example, cleaning work might seem a very menial and low-value activity.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] But if business equipment fails, customers stay away, and the staff get sick or injured, it costs the business a lot of extra money.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] In the *Grundrisse*, Marx also distinguished between "particular labour" and "general labour", contrasting communal production with production for exchange.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] Marx himself considered that all economising reduced to the economical use of human labour-time; "to economise" ultimately meant saving on human energy and effort.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] However, according to Marx, the achievement of abstract thinking about human labour, and the ability to quantify it, is closely related to the historical development of economic exchange in general, and more specifically commodity trade (the trade in wares and merchandise).
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] The expansion of trade requires the ability to measure and compare all kinds of things - not just length, volume and weight, but also time itself.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] Originally, the units of measurement used were taken from everyday life—the length of a finger or limb, the volume of an ordinary container, the weight one can carry, the duration of a day or a season, the number of cattle.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] In a biblical story where God delivers moral guidelines to Moses which people must follow, dishonest measures and mismeasurement are explicitly prohibited: “You shall do no wrong in judgment, in measures of length or weight or quantity.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] You shall have just balances, just weights…" (Leviticus 19:35).
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] Once standard measuring units existed, mathematics could begin to develop.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] In fact, Marx argues the abstraction of labour in thought is *the reflex of a real process*, in which commercial trade in products not only alters the way labour is *viewed*, but also how it is practically *treated*.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] In other words, when labour becomes a commercial object traded in the marketplace, then the form and content of work in the workplace is transformed as well, to conform to commercial requirements.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] This transformation is practically possible, because labour already contains the potential to adapt to the requirements of capitalist business.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] This potential has already been shaped up by previous schooling and training.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] Therefore, Marx implies, the exchange process itself *involves the making of a real abstraction*, namely abstraction from (or indifference to) the particular characteristics of concrete (specific) labour that produced the commodities whose value is equated in trade.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] At first, the relationship between quantities of traded commodities symbolically represents relative costs in labour time.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] This relationship is ordinarily quite transparent because goods are traded by the people who produced them.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] Next, money-prices begin to represent symbolically the commodities being traded.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] In this way, a system of symbolic representation emerges which can facilitate the exchange of the most diverse products with great efficiency.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] In the end, products as commodities become simply objects of value, and since their value can rise and fall, they can be bought and sold purely for capital gain.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] In a more complex division of labour, it becomes difficult or even impossible to equate the value of all different labour-efforts directly.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] But money enables us to express and compare the value of *all* different labour-efforts—more or less accurately—in money-units (initially, quantities of gold, silver, or bronze).
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] Marx then argues that labour viewed concretely in its specifics creates useful things, but labour-in-the-abstract is value-forming labour, which conserves, transfers and/or creates economic value (see Valorisation).
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] Quite simply, in this case, a quantity of labour-time is equal to a quantity of money, and it can be calculated that X hours of labour—regardless of who in particular performs them—create, or are worth, Y amounts of new product value.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] In this way, labour is *practically* rendered abstract.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] This is what Marx calls a *value relationship* ("Wertverhältnis" in German).
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] It can also be calculated that it costs a certain amount of time and money to train a worker to perform a certain task, and how much value that adds to the workers' labour, giving rise to the notion of human capital.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] As a corollary, in these conditions workers will increasingly treat the paid work they do as something distinct or separate from their personality, a means to an end rather than an end in itself.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] Work becomes "just work", it no longer *necessarily* says anything at all about the identity, creativity or personality of the worker.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] With the development of an average skill level in the workforce, the same job can also be done by many different workers, and most workers can do many different jobs; nobody is necessarily tied to one type of work all his life anymore.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] Thus we can talk of "a job" as an abstract function that could be filled by anybody with the required skills.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] Managers can calculate that with a certain budget, a certain number of paid working hours are required or available to do the work, and then divide up the hours into different job functions to be filled by suitably qualified personnel.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] Marx's theory of alienation considers the human and social implications of the abstraction and commercialization of labour.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] His concept of reification reflects about the inversions of object and subject, and of means and ends, which are involved in commodity trade.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] Marx regarded the distinction between abstract and concrete labour as being among the most important innovations he contributed to the theory of economic value, and subsequently Marxian scholars have debated a great deal about its theoretical significance.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] For ultraleftist Marxists, abstract labour is an economic category which applies only to the capitalist mode of production, i.e. it applies only, when human labour power or work-capacity is universally treated as a commodity with a certain monetary cost or earnings potential.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] The logical implication of this ultraleftist interpretation is, that if capitalism is destroyed (by the revolutionary Marxist Party and the working class), then abstract labour is also destroyed and eradicated.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] Other Marx-scholars, such as Makoto Itoh, take a more evolutionary view (like Marx did and archaeologists do).
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] Originally, in ancient society and medieval society ("premodern" or "pre-bourgeois" society), commodity production *co-existed* with subsistence production, a situation of "*partial* commodity production" (see also simple commodity production).
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] Such a division of labour featuring partial commodity production is already achieved in many different *precapitalist societies*, and consequently the category of abstract labour already existed in precapitalist societies.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] The category of abstract labour is fully realized because it becomes an objectified quantity.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] Another controversy concerns the differences between unskilled (simple) and skilled (qualified) labour.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] Skilled labour costs more to produce than unskilled labour, and can be more productive.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] This was reflected in a skill hierarchy, and a hierarchy of wage-levels.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] Marx believed that the capitalist mode of production would over time replace people with machines, and encourage the easy replacement of one worker by another, and thus that most labour would tend to reduce to an average skill level and standardized norms of work effort.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] However he provided no specific calculus by which the value of skilled work could be expressed as a multiple of unskilled work, nor a theory of what regulates the valuation of skill differences.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] This has led to some theoretical debate among Marxian economists, but no definitive solution has yet been given.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] In the first volume of *Das Kapital* Marx had declared his intention to write a special study of the forms of labour-compensation, but he never did so.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] In contemporary society, a division is emerging between creative, skilled and specialized jobs attracting extraordinarily large salaries, and routine jobs paying very low salaries, where the enormous differences in pay rates are difficult to explain.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] The economist Anwar Shaikh from the New School for Social Research has analyzed input-output data, wage data and labour data for the US economy, to create an *empirically testable* economic theory of the market valuation of skill differences.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] The counterargument is, that the valuation of skills in a heavily bureaucratized education system depends to a great extent on the *balance of class forces* between the rich educated class, and the "lower-skilled" working class.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] The rent-seeking educated class, on this view, can often raise its income far beyond the real worth of its work, if they occupy a privileged position, if its specialist skills happen to be in short supply or in demand, or if they are hired through the "old boy" networks.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] That is to say, to an extent, the assumed skill level of the employee may be more imaginary, than real; it all depends on how skills, experience and qualifications are defined and valued by privileged professionals whose rules reward their own kind the most.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] Skilled labour may be over-valued and unskilled labour under-valued at the same time.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] Marx did not think there was anything particularly mysterious about the fact that people valued products because they have to spend time working to produce them, or to buy them.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] However, academics have made many objections to his idea.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] The conceptual issues associated with the idea of abstract labour have been one of the main reasons why many economists abandoned the labour theory of value.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] It may be that the problems have never been resolved because they have been approached far too abstractly, using conceptual distinctions not really adequate for the purpose.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] Replying to this type of criticism, the Russian Marxist Isaak Illich Rubin argued that the concept of abstract labour was really much more complex than it seemed at first sight.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] He distinguished between "physically equal" labour, labour which is "socially equated" by means of consensual social evaluation or comparison, and labour efforts equated via the exchange of products using money as a universal equivalent.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] Some further aspects of the concept of abstract labour are provided by Marxian anthropologist Lawrence Krader and the mathematician Ulrich Krause.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] Possibly, these conceptual issues can be resolved, through a better empirical appreciation of the political economy of education, skills and the labour market.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] In his book *Crack Capitalism*, John Holloway considers abstract labour as the most radical foundational category of Marx's theory, and therefore he recommends the struggle against abstract labour as the centrepiece of the political struggle against capitalism.
[src:class-consciousness/abstract-labour-and-concrete-labour] The British computer scientist Paul Cockshott in 2013 wrote a piece critical of the German Marxist academic Michael Heinrich who, Cockshott argued, wrongly reinterpreted the concept of abstract labour so that it is no longer a scientifically testable concept.
[src:class-consciousness/class-consciousness] In sociology, **class consciousness** is the set of beliefs that persons hold regarding their social class or economic rank in society, the structure of their class, and their common class interests.
[src:class-consciousness/class-consciousness] According to Karl Marx, class consciousness is an awareness that is key to sparking a revolution which would "create a dictatorship of the proletariat, transforming it from a wage-earning, propertyless mass into the ruling class".
[src:class-consciousness/class-consciousness] Although Marxists tend to focus on class consciousness (or its absence) among the proletariat, the upper classes in society can also think and act in a class-conscious way.
[src:class-consciousness/class-consciousness] As Leonard Fein pointed out, "The very rich have been well aware of their class privilege and have laboured mightily to protect and defend it".
[src:class-consciousness/class-consciousness] Early in the 19th century, the labels "working classes" and "middle classes" were coming into common usage in British society.
[src:class-consciousness/class-consciousness] Categorizing a person's social class can be a determinant for their awareness of it.
[src:class-consciousness/class-consciousness] Marxists categorize classes based on their relation to the means of production, especially on whether members of the class own capital.
[src:class-consciousness/class-consciousness] Non-Marxists differentiate society's various groups based on social stratification, i.e., income, race, gender, ethnicity, education, occupation, or status.
[src:class-consciousness/class-consciousness] The Polish political philosopher Leszek Kołakowski disputed the notion that class consciousness could be instilled from outside by a vanguard party.
[src:class-consciousness/class-consciousness] In *Main Currents of Marxism* and his other writings, he stated that in order to achieve a unity of theory and praxis, theory must not only tend toward reality in an attempt to change it; reality must also tend towards theory.
[src:class-consciousness/class-consciousness] Otherwise, the historical process leads a life of its own, while theorists make their own little theories, desperately waiting for some kind of possible influence over the historical process.
[src:class-consciousness/class-consciousness] Henceforth, reality itself must tend toward the theory, making it the "expression of the revolutionary process itself".
[src:class-consciousness/class-consciousness] In turn, a theory which has as its goal helping the proletariat achieve class consciousness must first be an "objective theory of class consciousness".
[src:class-consciousness/class-consciousness] However, theory in itself is insufficient, and ultimately relies on the struggle of humankind and of the proletariat for consciousness: the "objective theory of class consciousness is only the theory of its objective possibility".
[src:class-consciousness/class-consciousness] Austrian School economist Ludwig von Mises asserted that "Marx confus[ed] the notions of caste and class".
[src:class-consciousness/class-consciousness] Mises believed that under capitalism, one's wealth should not affect how one is treated by legislators, law enforcement, or the courts.
